    {
      "text": "Under the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act (CFAA), 18 U.S.C. § 1030, a former employee uses their previously assigned credentials to access their former employer's database three months after termination to retrieve personal files they had stored on the company server. The employer had not yet deactivated the account. Which of the following best describes the legal status of this access under the CFAA?",
      "tag": "cfaa_unauthorized_access_exceeds_authorized_access",
      "options": [
        "A. The access is unauthorized under 18 U.S.C. § 1030(a)(2) because authorization terminated with employment, regardless of whether credentials were revoked",
        "B. The access is authorized because the employer failed to revoke credentials, demonstrating implicit continued authorization under agency principles",
        "C. The access violates only state computer trespass laws, not the CFAA, because the employee accessed only their own personal files",
        "D. The access constitutes exceeding authorized access under 18 U.S.C. § 1030(a)(4) only if the employee obtained information for commercial advantage or private financial gain"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "Under the CFAA, authorization is typically tied to the employment relationship and the employer's access policies. When employment terminates, the former employee's authorization to access the employer's computer systems also terminates, even if technical access remains possible due to the employer's failure to revoke credentials. Courts have consistently held that accessing a computer system after authorization has been revoked or terminated constitutes 'unauthorized access' under 18 U.S.C. § 1030(a)(2). The termination of employment ends the agency relationship and any authority to access employer systems, making subsequent access unauthorized regardless of whether credentials still function. This principle was reinforced in cases like LVRC Holdings LLC v. Brekka and United States v. Rodriguez, which examined the scope of authorization under the CFAA.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B is incorrect because the employer's administrative failure to revoke credentials does not create implicit authorization; authorization depends on the employment relationship and access policies, not technical capability. Option C is incorrect because the CFAA applies to unauthorized access regardless of what files are accessed, and federal jurisdiction exists when the computer is used in interstate commerce. Option D is incorrect because 18 U.S.C. § 1030(a)(2) prohibits unauthorized access to obtain information without requiring proof of commercial advantage or financial gain; that element applies specifically to subsection (a)(4) involving fraud, which is a separate violation.",
      "num": 1,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "law_cfe/quiz_006_en.json"
    },
