      "question": "A fraudster sets up a fake website that mimics a legitimate bank's login page, sends phishing emails to customers directing them to the site, and captures their usernames and passwords when they attempt to log in. The fraudster then uses these credentials to transfer funds from victims' accounts. Which of the following BEST describes the primary identity theft technique used in this scenario?",
      "options": {
        "A": "Pretexting through social engineering to obtain sensitive information directly from bank employees",
        "B": "Phishing to harvest authentication credentials through a fraudulent website",
        "C": "Skimming devices installed on ATM machines to capture card data",
        "D": "Dumpster diving to obtain discarded bank statements containing account information"
      },
      "correct_answer": "B",
      "explanation": "This scenario describes a classic phishing attack where the fraudster creates a fake website (spoofing) to deceive victims into voluntarily entering their credentials. Phishing is a form of social engineering that uses fraudulent emails and fake websites to harvest sensitive information. Option A is incorrect because pretexting involves creating a fabricated scenario to extract information, typically through direct communication. Option C is incorrect because skimming involves physical devices that capture data from card magnetic stripes. Option D is incorrect because this scenario involves electronic fraud rather than physical theft of discarded documents.",
