      "correct_answer": "B",
      "explanation": "This scenario describes a Business Email Compromise (BEC) or CEO fraud scheme, where attackers impersonate executives to authorize fraudulent payments. The most effective preventive control is implementing dual authorization requirements for fund transfers, which ensures that no single person can complete a wire transfer without independent verification. This would have caught the fraud even though the employee was deceived by the social engineering. Multi-factor authentication (A) helps prevent account takeover but wouldn't stop an employee from acting on a fraudulent email. DDoS attacks (C) and SQL injection (D) are different types of cyber attacks unrelated to this scenario.",
